##The Dow Jones Industrial Average plunged nearly 900 points as the CDC issued a new alert for the outbreak

CDC Tuesday warned that the new pneumonia outbreak will continue to spread, urging businesses, schools and communities to prepare for a possible outbreak. On the same day, the U. S. stocks were again heavily sold, panic index continued to climb, bonds and other safe assets were sought after.

Tuesday closed Dow Jones Industrial Average down 879.44 points, or 3.15% , at 27,081.36, a two day plunge of more than 1,900 points. The Nasdaq was down 255.67 points, or 2.77% , at 8,965.61. The S & P 500 was down 97.68 points, or 3.03% , at 3,128.21. The yield on the benchmark 10-year note fell 2.5 basis points to 1.352 per cent, hitting an all-time low of 1.307 per cent, with bond prices inversely correlated with yields.

The Chicago Board Options Exchange, a gauge of market panic, continued to rise to 27.85, or 11.27% , after briefly breaking the 30 mark.

"The scale of the economic impact seems to be expanding globally, " James Eich Athey, senior investment manager at Aberdeen Standard Investments, told The Wall Street Journal. "There are cracks in stock markets that have been driven by sentiment. "

Tuesday, head of the CDC's Center for Immunization and Respiratory Disease Control, says the new coronavirus is likely to spread in the community. "It's just a matter of time, " she said, adding that the agency was preparing for it and encouraging people to start planning for it. The CDC also warned that in the coming weeks, the Department of Health will have to suspend schools and businesses if the virus starts spreading in communities in the United States.

As of February 24,53 cases of new pneumonia had been confirmed in the United States, including 36 evacuees from the Japanese "Diamond Princess" cruise ship, 3 evacuees from Wuhan, China, and 14 confirmed cases in the United States.

Symon Powell Simon Powell, Equity Strategist at Jefferies & Company Jefferies, said in an interview with CNBC: "We are finding it increasingly difficult to believe that the number of confirmed cases in the US is as low as reported, given the number of Chinese, Koreans and Italians entering North America, and that the likelihood of a large-scale outbreak in the US community is increasing... if it is not managed properly, it will cause great volatility in the market. "

According to The Wall Street Journal, the White House has asked Congress for at least $2.5 billion to fight the epidemic, including $1.25 billion in additional funds and $500 million that would have been used to fight the Zaire ebolavirus. The money will be used to develop vaccines, buy protective equipment and so on.

As of 10:00 central European time on February 24,29 countries outside China had reported a total of 2,069 confirmed cases and 23 deaths, according to the WHO outbreak report. Tan Desai, WHO director-general, said that while the sharp increase in new cases of pneumonia in Italy, Iran and South Korea was deeply worrying, the outbreak had not yet constituted a "pandemic" .

Major European indexes Tuesday closed down, with Italy's FTSE MIB down 1.44% , FRANCE'S CAC 40 down 1.94% , Germany's DAX down 1.88% and Britain's FTSE 100 down 1.94% .

International oil prices continue to fall. Tuesday closed 3 percent lower at $49.90 a barrel for West Texas intermediate and 2.4 percent lower at $54.95 a barrel for Brent Crude.

International gold prices also weakened sharply, and there were clear signs of profit-taking. Tuesday closed the day with April gold, the most traded commodity on the New York Mercantile Exchange, down $26.60, or 1.59 percent, to $1,650 an ounce.
